=== Parliamentary QA ===
Title: Data on Repeated Vaping Offenders in Schools and IHLs in Last Five Years and Prevention for Curbing Addiction
Date: 7 February 2024
Document Type: Parliamentary QA (Written Answer)
Topic: Repeat vaping offenders and cessation programmes

Summary:

- Question:
  (a) Number and proportion of repeat vaping offenders in schools and IHLs over the last five years.
  (b) Differentiated help programmes for re-offenders and their families.
  (c) Effectiveness of these programmes in curbing vaping addiction among youths.

- MOH/HSA/HPB Response:
  1. Repeat offenders:
     - Between 2019â€“2023, there were 813 repeat offenders under 18.
     - This constituted 25% of all offenders under 18.
  2. Preventive education and cessation support:
     - HPB works with MOE, schools, and IHLs.
     - Programmes include QuitLine, tele-counselling, and on-site counselling via Student Health Advisors (SHAs).
  3. Programme focus:
     - Educate youths on harms of smoking and vaping.
     - Teach strategies to quit and manage withdrawal symptoms.
  4. Programme effectiveness (2023 data):
     - 2,350 youths received cessation counselling.
     - 38% reduced or quit smoking/vaping one month post-counselling.

Key Entities:
- Ministry of Health (MOH)
- Health Sciences Authority (HSA)
- Health Promotion Board (HPB)
- Ministry of Education (MOE)
- Schools and Institutes of Higher Learning (IHLs)
- Student Health Advisors (SHAs)

Key Concepts:
- Repeat offender monitoring
- Preventive education and cessation support
- Tele-counselling and on-site counselling
- Behavioural change and withdrawal management
- Outcome measurement of cessation programmes
